\pard\plain\ltrpar\ql\fi-547\li273\ri274\s53\sl280\slmult0\itap0\tqdec\tx80\tx260\tx875\tx1595\tx2315\tx3035\tx3755\tx4475\tx5195\tx5915\tx6635\tx7355\tx8075\tx8358{\s53\f0\fs22\lang1033{\*\listtag0}\abinodiroverride\ltrch \tab 1.\tab Let us speak of landscapes and looks, turning once again to what was said in the beginning: \uc1\u8220\'93External landscape is what we perceive of things, while internal landscape is what we sift from them through the sieve of our internal world. These landscapes are one and constitute our indissoluble vision of reality.\uc1\u8221\'94 }{\s53\f0\fs22\lang1033{\*\listtag0}\par}
\pard\plain\ltrpar\ql\fi-547\li273\ri274\s53\sl280\slmult0\itap0\tqdec\tx80\tx260\tx875\tx1595\tx2315\tx3035\tx3755\tx4475\tx5195\tx5915\tx6635\tx7355\tx8075\tx8358{\s53\f0\fs22\lang1033{\*\listtag0}\abinodiroverride\ltrch \tab 2.\tab Beginning with the perception of an external object, a naive look may confuse \uc1\u8220\'93what is seen\uc1\u8221\'94 with reality itself. Some go further, believing that they remember \uc1\u8220\'93reality\uc1\u8221\'94 just as it was. And still others confuse objects they have perceived and then transformed in other states of consciousness (their illusions, hallucinations, or dream images) with material objects.}{\s53\f0\fs22\lang1033{\*\listtag0}\par}
\pard\plain\ltrpar\ql\fi-547\li273\ri274\s53\sl280\slmult0\itap0\tqdec\tx80\tx260\tx875\tx1595\tx2315\tx3035\tx3755\tx4475\tx5195\tx5915\tx6635\tx7355\tx8075\tx8358{\s53\f0\fs22\lang1033{\*\listtag0}\abinodiroverride\ltrch \tab 3.\tab It is not difficult for reasonable people to understand that objects perceived in an earlier moment can appear distorted in dreams and memories. But the simplicity of daily action, of doing with and among things, is shaken to its core by the idea that perceived objects are }{\s53\f0\fs22\i\lang1033{\*\listtag0}always}{\s53\f0\fs22\lang1033{\*\listtag0} covered by a multicolored mantle woven of other, simultaneous perceptions and memories; that perception is an overall mode of }{\s53\f0\fs22\i\lang1033{\*\listtag0}being-in-the-midst-of-things,}{\s53\f0\fs22\lang1033{\*\listtag0} and includes an emotional tone and the general state of one\uc1\u8217\'92s body.}{\s53\f0\fs22\lang1033{\*\listtag0}\par}
\pard\plain\ltrpar\ql\fi-547\li273\ri274\s53\sl280\slmult0\itap0\tqdec\tx80\tx260\tx875\tx1595\tx2315\tx3035\tx3755\tx4475\tx5195\tx5915\tx6635\tx7355\tx8075\tx8358{\s53\f0\fs22\lang1033{\*\listtag0}\abinodiroverride\ltrch \tab 4.\tab The naive look grasps the \uc1\u8220\'93external\uc1\u8221\'94 world along with its own pain or its own joy. I do not look with my eyes alone, but also with my heart, with gentle recollection, with ominous suspicion, with cold calculation, with stealthy comparison. I look through allegories, signs, and symbols, and though I do not see these things in my looking, they act on it nonetheless, just as when I look I do not see my eye or its activity. }{\s53\f0\fs22\lang1033{\*\listtag0}\par}
\pard\plain\ltrpar\ql\fi-547\li273\ri274\s53\sl280\slmult0\itap0\tqdec\tx80\tx260\tx875\tx1595\tx2315\tx3035\tx3755\tx4475\tx5195\tx5915\tx6635\tx7355\tx8075\tx8358{\s53\f0\fs22\lang1033{\*\listtag0}\abinodiroverride\ltrch \tab 5.\tab Because of the complexity of perceiving, I prefer to use the word }{\s53\f0\fs22\i\lang1033{\*\listtag0}landscape}{\s53\f0\fs22\lang1033{\*\listtag0} rather than }{\s53\f0\fs22\i\lang1033{\*\listtag0}object}{\s53\f0\fs22\lang1033{\*\listtag0} when speaking of reality, whether external or internal. And with that, I take it as given that I am referring to complexes and structures, and not to objects in some isolated and abstract individuality. }{\s53\f0\fs22\lang1033{\*\listtag0}\par}
\pard\plain\ltrpar\ql\fi244\li274\ri274\s44\sl280\slmult0\itap0\tqdec\tx80\tx260\tx1595\tx2315\tx3755\tx4475\tx5915\tx6635\tx8075\tx8358{\s44\f0\fs22\lang1033{\*\listtag0}\abinodiroverride\ltrch I want to emphasize, too, that these landscapes correspond to acts of perception that I call }{\s44\f0\fs22\i\lang1033{\*\listtag0}looks }{\s44\f0\fs22\lang1033{\*\listtag0}(encroaching, perhaps illegitimately, on fields unrelated to visualization). These looks are active and complex acts that organize landscapes. They are not simple passive acts of receiving external information (data that arrive through my external senses) or internal information (that is, sensations from my own body, memories, apperceptions). }{\s44\f0\fs22\lang1033{\*\listtag0}\par}
\pard\plain\ltrpar\ql\fi244\li274\ri274\s44\sl280\slmult0\itap0\tqdec\tx80\tx260\tx1595\tx2315\tx3755\tx4475\tx5915\tx6635\tx8075\tx8358{\s44\f0\fs22\lang1033{\*\listtag0}\abinodiroverride\ltrch There should be no need to add that in these mutual interrelations between looks and landscapes, the distinction between internal and external is drawn on the basis of the direction of the intentionality of the consciousness\uc1\u8212\'97and not as is frequently set forth in the naive schemata that are presented to schoolchildren.}{\s44\f0\fs22\lang1033{\*\listtag0}\par}
\pard\plain\ltrpar\ql\fi-547\li273\ri274\s53\sl280\slmult0\itap0\tqdec\tx80\tx260\tx875\tx1595\tx2315\tx3035\tx3755\tx4475\tx5195\tx5915\tx6635\tx7355\tx8075\tx8358{\s53\f0\fs22\lang1033{\*\listtag0}\abinodiroverride\ltrch \tab 6.\tab If you have understood the foregoing, you will also understand that when I speak of the human landscape I am referring to a type of external landscape that is composed of people and\uc1\u8212\'97even on those occasions when the human being }{\s53\f0\fs22\i\lang1033{\*\listtag0}per se}{\s53\f0\fs22\lang1033{\*\listtag0} is absent\uc1\u8212\'97human acts and intentions made manifest in objects.}{\s53\f0\fs22\lang1033{\*\listtag0}\par}
\pard\plain\ltrpar\ql\fi-547\li273\ri274\s53\sl280\slmult0\itap0\tqdec\tx80\tx260\tx875\tx1595\tx2315\tx3035\tx3755\tx4475\tx5195\tx5915\tx6635\tx7355\tx8075\tx8358{\s53\f0\fs22\lang1033{\*\listtag0}\abinodiroverride\ltrch \tab 7.\tab It is important, then, to distinguish between the }{\s53\f0\fs22\i\lang1033{\*\listtag0}internal world}{\s53\f0\fs22\lang1033{\*\listtag0} and }{\s53\f0\fs22\i\lang1033{\*\listtag0}internal landscape,}{\s53\f0\fs22\lang1033{\*\listtag0} between }{\s53\f0\fs22\i\lang1033{\*\listtag0}nature}{\s53\f0\fs22\lang1033{\*\listtag0} and }{\s53\f0\fs22\i\lang1033{\*\listtag0}external landscape,}{\s53\f0\fs22\lang1033{\*\listtag0} between }{\s53\f0\fs22\i\lang1033{\*\listtag0}society}{\s53\f0\fs22\lang1033{\*\listtag0} and }{\s53\f0\fs22\i\lang1033{\*\listtag0}human landscape.}{\s53\f0\fs22\lang1033{\*\listtag0} What I am trying to emphasize is that to speak of landscapes always implies }{\s53\f0\fs22\i\lang1033{\*\listtag0}one who looks,}{\s53\f0\fs22\lang1033{\*\listtag0} as opposed to situations in which the internal (psychological) world, nature, or society are naively taken as existing in themselves, independent of any interpretation. }{\*\bkmkstart _Toc31381209}{\*\bkmkstart _Toc31381383}{\s53\f0\fs22\lang1033{\*\listtag0}\par}
